{    Introduction    }
^-|fp||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|Welcome to my lesson on ^*IHow to Make Effective Raises in Competition^*N. Competitive bidding is often misunderstood by many less experienced players. Competitive bidding occurs on half the hands you play or even more.  |
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


AT|

Many players use high card points as their primary means of deciding how and when to compete but this is incorrect. High Card Points are only a (very) small part of the picture. Distribution and fit with partner are much more important. In this lesson, I am going to focus on one part of competing, that is, what to do in the happy case when you have found a fit with partner.|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


AT|

The lesson is divided into several parts. First, I will discuss general guidelines for competing. Then I will discuss how to compete after an  overcall (suit bid by the opponent). I will differentiate between what to do when you have a major suit fit vs a minor suit fit. Then I will discuss what to do after your Right Hand Opponent (RHO) makes a takeout double. Again, differentiating between whether partner opened a major or a minor.|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


AT|

In each section I have many example hands. So let us get started.|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


NT||
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%Guidelines and the LAW
qx|B2, Guidelines and the Law|ht|b|cs|6|AT|^-{    General Competitive Guidelines and the Law of Total Tricks    }
^-|AT|^B@2
The single most important guideline is the ^*ILaw of Total Tricks^*N also known as LOTT. I focus first on LOTT (Bergen version) which says the following:|
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


AT|
^-
{    IT IS SAFE  TO  COMPETE TO THE SAME  LEVEL AS THE ## OF TRUMPS YOUR SIDE HAS.    }
^-|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


at|

So if you have an 8-card fit, you can compete to the 2-level (8 trick contract). With a 9-card  fit, feel free to compete to the 3-level. And with a 10-card fit, compete to the 4-level.|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


AT|

The LAW is a really good guideline. It is  much better even than most expert judgement despite what you may have heard. There are occasional hands where it is off by a trick but they are few and far between. If you use the law, you will do well. I do and I think I bid very effectively in competition.|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


AT|

By the way, the LAW as I stated it is actually not the pure "Law of Total Tricks", but it is very practical and works well.|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


AT|

Next I would like to tell you what the pure "Law of Total Tricks" says.|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


AT| The pure "Law of Total Tricks" says the following:

^-{
    FOR EACH SIDE, TAKE THE NUMBER OF CARDS THEY HAVE IN THEIR LONGEST SUIT.    
     ADD THOSE 2 NUMBERS TOGETHER. 
     THAT NUMBER WILL GIVE YOU THE TOTAL NUMBER OF TRICKS      
IN THE DEAL IF EACH SIDE PLAYED IN THEIR LONGEST SUIT.
}^-|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


AT|

For example, if you have a 9-card fit and they have an 8-card fit, the total tricks is 17 (9+8). Then if you can make 4 (10 tricks) the other side can only make 1 (17-10 = 7). |
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


AT|

In  real life that is too complicated. If interested, however, Larry Cohen wrote an excellent book on the Law which has many charts and tables.|
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


NT||
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%Page 
HT|B|cp|1|AT|^B@2^*BMM: ^*N|cp||at|The book is available from his web site along with a short explanation of the LAW. You can click|CP|1|AT|^*Hwww.larryco.com/BridgeArticles/ArticleDetails.aspx?articleID=229^*N|CP||
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


AT|

Further there is a nice and short write up on the LAW by Wikipedia base on Mr. Cohen at
|CP|1|AT|^*Hen.wikipedia.org/wiki/Law_of_total_tricks^*N|
pg| ***** 15 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|The pure version is much more complicated than the Bergen approach. It is almost impossible for you to know how many trumps the Opponents have. Therefore, the pure Law of Total Tricks, although theoretically interesting, is not particularly practical.|
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


AT|

The Bergen approach, however, is very practical. If you just focus on  how many trump you have, you will know how high to bid. That is simple, easy to apply, and most importantly, extremely effective.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


AT|

Its most important application is in the 2-level and 3-level cases. I have some very simple, but very good guidelines about that. I am sure you may have heard the saying "The 3 level belongs to the opponents." and there is some truth to that, so long as you understand how to compete.|
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


AT|

Let us first talk about bidding "3 over 3." That means, if the opponents have found a fit, and they are at the 3 level, and your fit is in a higher ranking suit should you bid 3 or not?|
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


AT|

The answer is you should bid "3 over 3" only in the following circumstances:|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


ht|r|cp|1|AT|
a) you know you have a 9-card fit or |
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


ht|r|AT|
a) you know you have a 9-card fit or 
b) you have a singleton or void in their suit.|
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


cp||AT|

Those are the only times it is right to bid 3 over 3 for the most part. In IMPs that is always true. In Match Points, that is generally true, but it is in fact a bit more tricky. In IMPs, if you follow that rule, even if you can make 3, the opponents will likely be going down so you will get a plus score if you deserve one. However, in Match Points, if you can make 3, sometimes the opponents will go down less than your score for making 3.|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


AT|

Having said that, I still think my guidelines are good even in Match Points. You will still be right more often than you are wrong. Often when you bid "3 over 3" neither side can make 3. Therefore, you turned a plus into a minus.|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


NT||
